height=3D"227" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"494" data-file-=
height=3D"448"></a><figcaption>Stem and leaf diagram (a.k.a stemplot) repre=
senting the number of birds at a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
atering_hole" title=3D"Watering hole">watering hole</a> each hour.</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>A <b>stem-and-leaf display</b> or <b>stem-and-leaf plot</b> is a device =
for  presenting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantitative_data"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantitative data">quantitative data</a> in=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_graphics" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Information graphics">graphical</a> format, similar t=
o a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histogram" title=3D"Histogram"=
>histogram</a>, to assist in visualizing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Shape" title=3D"Shape">shape</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution"=
>distribution</a>. They evolved from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Arthur_Bowley" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arthur Bowley">Arthur Bowl=
ey</a>'s work in the early 1900s, and are useful tools in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploratory_data_analysis" title=3D"Exploratory dat=
a analysis">exploratory data analysis</a>. Stemplots became more commonly u=
sed in the 1980s after the publication of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/John_Tukey" title=3D"John Tukey">John Tukey</a>'s book on <i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploratory_data_analysis" title=3D"Expl=
oratory data analysis">exploratory data analysis</a></i> in 1977.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tem-and-leaf_display#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The popularity during those ye=
ars is attributable to their use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Monospaced" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Monospaced">monospaced</a> (ty=
pewriter) typestyles that allowed computer technology of the time to easily=
 produce the graphics. Modern computers' superior graphic capabilities have=
 meant these techniques are less often used.
</p><p>This plot has been implemented in Octave<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stem-and-leaf_displ=
ay#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> and R.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stem-and-leaf_display#cite_note-3=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>A stem-and-leaf plot is also called a <b>stemplot</b>, but the latte=
r term often refers to another chart type.  A simple stem plot may refer to=
 plotting a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix</a> of <i>y</i> values onto a common =
<i>x</i> axis, and identifying the common<i> x</i> value with a vertical li=
ne, and the individual <i>y </i>values with symbols on the line.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St=
em-and-leaf_display#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Unlike histograms, stem-and-leaf displays retain the original data t=
o at least two significant digits, and put the data in order, thereby easin=
g the move to order-based inference and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Non-parametric_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-paramet=
ric statistics">non-parametric statistics</a>.
<br>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Construction">Construction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStem-and-lea=
f_display&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Constru=
ction"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>To construct a stem-and-leaf display, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Observations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Observations">obser=
vations</a> must first be sorted in ascending order: this can be done most =
easily if working by hand by constructing a draft of the stem-and-leaf disp=
lay with the leaves unsorted, then sorting the leaves to produce the final =
stem-and-leaf display. Here is the sorted set of data values that will be u=
sed in the following example:
</p>
<dl><dd>44, 46, 47, 49, 63, 64, 66, 68, 68, 72, 72, 75, 76, 81, 84, 88, 106=
</dd></dl>
<p>Next, it must be determined what the stems will represent and what the l=
eaves will represent. Typically, the leaf contains the last digit of the nu=
mber and the stem contains all of the other digits. In the case of very lar=
ge numbers, the data values may be rounded to a particular <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Place_value" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Place =
value">place value</a> (such as the hundreds place) that will be used for t=
he leaves. The remaining digits to the left of the rounded place value are =
used as the stem.
</p><p>In this example, the leaf represents the ones place and the stem wil=
l represent the rest of the number (tens place and higher).
</p><p>The stem-and-leaf display is drawn with two columns separated by a v=
ertical line. The stems are listed to the left of the vertical line. It is =
important that each stem is listed only once and that no numbers are skippe=
d, even if it means that some stems have no leaves. The leaves are listed i=
n increasing order in a row to the right of each stem.
</p><p>When there is a repeated number in the data (such as two 72s), the p=
lot must reflect such (so the plot would look like 7 | 2 2 5 6 7 when it ha=
s the numbers 72 72 75 76 77).
</p>
