<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Usage">Usage</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStem-and-leaf_display&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Usage"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Stem-and-leaf displays are useful for displaying the relative density an=
d shape of the data, giving the reader a quick overview of the distribution=
. They retain (most of) the raw numerical data, often with perfect integrit=
y. They are also useful for highlighting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a> and finding the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_(statistics)" title=3D"Mode (statistics)"=
>mode</a>. However, stem-and-leaf displays are only useful for moderately s=
ized data sets (around 15=E2=80=93150 data points). With very small data se=
ts a stem-and-leaf displays can be of little use, as a reasonable number of=
 data points are required to establish definitive distribution properties. =
A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_plot_(statistics)" title=3D"=
Dot plot (statistics)">dot plot</a> may be better suited for such data. Wit=
h very large data sets, a stem-and-leaf display will become very cluttered,=
 since each data point must be represented numerically. A <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot" title=3D"Box plot">box plot</a> or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histogram" title=3D"Histogram">histogram=
</a> may become more appropriate as the data size increases.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Non-numerical_use">Non-nume=
rical use</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSt=
